From 377e3e552ae487a06a845daf947e0541d2bcb6cf Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Volker Badziong <development@richtfest.tech>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 06:45:23 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 4/7] Manage per-server transient slices via systemd D-Bus

With docker.per_server_slices.enabled, every server is placed under its own
derived slice (cgroup_parent + dashless server UUID, nesting via systemd
dash naming) and Wings ensures that slice exists as a transient unit --
carrying the node-wide default resource properties (memory.min/low/high/max
floors and ceilings, cpu/io weights) merged with admin-only per-server
WINGS_CG_* overrides -- before any container is placed under it. Without
this, systemd materializes the slice limit-less at placement time: the
cgroup path looks right while every guarantee is silently absent.

Properties go exclusively through the systemd D-Bus API
(StartTransientUnit/SetUnitProperties runtime=true), the reload-safe
channel; raw cgroupfs writes can be wiped by daemon-reload.

A configurable memory_min_budget bounds the sum of floors Wings hands out,
because child floors beyond the parent slice's own MemoryMin are
arithmetically dead. budget_policy decides what happens when a request
exceeds the remainder: clamp reduces it to what is left, refuse drops the
floor rather than grant a smaller one, and distribute applies it as asked
and lets the kernel share the parent's protection in proportion to each
child's usage below its own floor. Every other property is applied
unchanged under all three.

Slice management is strictly best-effort: D-Bus failures degrade to plain
placement with a logged warning and never block a server.

An explicit WINGS_CGROUP_PARENT override remains supported and marks the
slice hand-managed (only explicit WINGS_CG_* values applied, never node
defaults); overriding with exactly the node-wide value opts a server out.
Derived slices of deleted servers are stopped on delete and orphans are
garbage-collected at boot; administrator unit-file slices are never
touched.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
